I actually have kind of the same problem in one of my projects. I need to generate `TypeScript` or `JSDoc-JavaScript` code.
I'm doing this by calling some helper functions that output the code in the specific syntax or nothing if it doesn't match the configured syntax.

I write normal `JavaScript` code and then sprinkle in those functions where needed. Not the prettiest code but it works ^^

See an example [here](https://github.com/ivanhofer/typesafe-i18n/blob/main/packages/generator/src/files/generate-adapter-svelte.ts#L34)
[generated output](https://github.com/ivanhofer/typesafe-i18n/blob/main/packages/generator/test/generated/adapter-svelte/svelte.expected.ts) for `TypeScript` 
[generated output](https://github.com/ivanhofer/typesafe-i18n/blob/main/packages/generator/test/generated/adapter-svelte-jsdoc/svelte.expected.js) for `JavaScript`

An improved solution would probably be something like this where you write e.g. a function in an abstract form and let it generate the correct syntax:

```ts
function({
   name: 'myFunction',
   params: [{ id: 'string' }],
   returns: 'string',
   body: 'return id'
)

// generated TypeScript code
const myFunction = (id: string): string=> {
   return id
}

// generated JavaScript code
/**
 * @param { string } id
 * @return string
 */
const myFunction = (id) => {
   return id
}
```
But such an approach would make it harder for new contributions because they would need to learn how to use such an abstraction.

But writing it in plain `TypeScript` and `Javascript` and having to keep two different examples in sync would also be a challenging task.

